<br>
This is essentially a personal viewpoint, though.  Every item and every character I have and have had since EQ release has all been earned in-game.  Other people take a wider view of the definition of &quot;game&quot; and include that to mean paying RL$$ for things or blowing the GL to get him to twink your ranger.<br>
<br>
Everyone has a set of lines drawn over which they won't cross.  The stigmata of &quot;ebayness&quot; only enters the picture when someone else is crossing lines you would't cross.  While it's not necessarily valid to generalize one line crossing into crossing ALL lines and being a complete psychotic, it's certainly a human tendancy to do so.  That's where the distrust of ebay's comes in; ie. if he'll buy a character for money (which I think is wrong), what's to stop him from training me out of my rare camp (which I also thing is wrong)?<br>
<br>
The answer is always the same, though: nothing will stop him.  He'll either stop himself or he won't.  Until you get to know where someone's lines are drawn, you really can't just live by a few gross generalizations.<br>
<br>
BTW, as far as legality goes on ebay, don't make me laugh.  Are you permitted to give plat and items to someone in game for free?  Yes.  Are there any rules that govern the reasons that could make you decide to give someone plat or items?  No.  Therefor, selling items/plat in game is just fine.  You aren't selling the intellectual property of SOE.  That would mean you are trying to grant someone the right to copy an item or feature for another game.  You're selling the transfer of the item.  SOE explicitly permits you to trade items for whatever reason takes your fancy.  Just because you don't like something and would not do it yourself does not make it illegal.<br>
<br>
Transfer of account is something different and I think SOE could make a case of that.  I also think you could make a case for transfer being OK.  I'm not a lawyer, but I've been involved directly and indirectly in enough license battles to have a rather thorough disgust for the ambiguity of the laws there. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stavehamvaliant@firionavie>StavehamValiant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 138<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/2/03 9:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=43.topic&index=51>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: As far as whether someone is &quot;ebay&quot; or not ..</span><hr size=1> Nidge, while you may not see the difference, the Law does.<br>
<br>
If you sell in game plat (which belongs, leagally to Sony, your just paying for the righ to use it) for real life money, you've sold Sony's property for prophit. Sony doesn't see any of that money. When you buy software, you are only buying the right to use that software, under thier terms. You don't actually own the software. So, selling in game, Sony owned plat or items for real life money, is selling something you don't own.<br>
<br>
If some one draws a picture, they own it. In no way does Sony own it. So the person that drew the picture can do with it what they want. Trading a sig picture for in game plat doesn't not create a prophit for the person in real life that drew the picture. There is the difference in the Laws eyes. And yes, while you are trading Sony own plat for an item, that sig picture has no resale value, which is what it comes down to. So there is nothing to be gained from it.<br>
<br>
No one ever said the Law was always right.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caillougna>Caillou GNA</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.tshrew.net/caillou/sigs/dot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pebble with a bow</span><br>  Posts: 1613<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/2/03 11:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=43.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: As far as whether someone is &quot;ebay&quot; or not ..</span><hr size=1> Personally, I think the paying in plat for a sig picture skirts the line.  The only reason I think it doesn't cross it entirely (but only in my opinion, of course) is because a sig is for the character which is the in-game personality.<br>
<br>
About changing the name... I keep hearing the e-bayers wanting people to not notice their ebaying, so... changing the name does achieve that.  Keeping the same name -does- stamp a &quot;bought on ebay (or whereever)&quot; on your forehead, especially to those who once knew the original person behind the character.  If you want to be regarded as a new or different character, changing the name accomplishes this in spades.  As for the car analogy... when you buy a car you also allocate enough money for the insurance and licensing fees when you are figuring out what you can afford.  Consider the price of changing the name as part of the processing fee and allocate your funds accordingly.  Then you not only keep your ebaying practice hushed, you also don't stamp &quot;bought on ebay&quot; on your forehead and give a bit of comfort to those who once knew the original.  But, I guess we're supposed to give you all considerations and you give us none... bleah.<br>
<br>
Anyone who brags about buying or selling a character has little respect from me and any respect I did have is instantly eroded.  Anyone who posts a good-bye indicating they are selling likewise will have a hard time re-earning my respect if they remain in game with another account/character.  I could careless if the person stripped the character of the &quot;good stuff&quot; and gave it away to fellow guildmates and other friends before selling out and didn't do anything to gather more goods on the backs of others in order to get a better buy price, they still sold out and I still disagree and I still have NO respect for the practice.<br>
<br>
It is nice to know, though, that there are still a few others who don't accept the practice as good or okay or normal.  Sadly, I think the number is dwindling. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#A62A2A>- </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie>Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49>The Dead Horse Forum</a> <font color=#A62A2A> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.3u<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  